To differentiate \( \tan x \) with regard to \( x \). 
Let \( y = \tan x \) and \( y - y(1 + 8x) \) then \(\tan(1 + 8x)\). 

\begin{align*}
\frac{dy}{dx} &= \frac{\sin((1 + 8x) \cdot \cos((1 + 8x))}{\cos^2(8x) \\ 
&= \frac{\sin(8x) \cdot \cos((1 + 8x))}{\cos^2(8x)}
\end{align*}

Dividing through by \( \cos(8x) \): 
\frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{\sin(8x) }{\cos^2(8x)} 
\quad as \( x \to 0 \): \quad x \to 0 \quad = \sec^2 x
